    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay thanks. i think it might be the capacitor thing u mentioned. if i turn the power off and open it up, how do i actually tell if the capacitor is bad? is there a specific look or smell i should be looking for?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You can often diagnose a bad capacitor by checking for visible damage like bulging, leaking oil, or a low or missing \"thump-pthump\" sound when first flipped on (though you won't hear this if power is off to test it safely). While it usually smells fine, be aware that if it's leaking, there may be a faint oily smell or an oily spot on the fins. Because capacitors store a deadly charge even when disconnected, this is not a DIY repair and requires a multimeter or a replacements kit; if you are unsure, call a professional to avoid electric shock.",
